'''Aiden Connor O'Neill''' (born 4 July 1998) is an Australian professional [[association football|soccer]] player who currently plays as a [[defensive midfielder]] for [[New York City FC]] and the [[Australia men's national soccer team|Australia national team]].

Born in Brisbane, O'Neill played youth football for Kenmore F.C. (now called [[University of Queensland FC|UQFC]]), then Brisbane Athletic and [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]] before making his professional debut for the latter in 2016. He spent some time on loan to [[Oldham Athletic A.F.C.|Oldham Athletic]] and [[Fleetwood Town F.C.|Fleetwood Town]], scoring his first ever professional goal for the latter club. He returned to Australia, on loan, to play for [[Central Coast Mariners FC|Central Coast Mariners]] in 2018.

He previously represented the [[Australia men's national under-23 soccer team|Australian under-23 national team]].

==Early life==
O'Neill  was born and raised in Brisbane, attending Nudgee Junior College before moving to [[Brisbane Boys' College]] before moving to England aged fourteen when his parents moved there for work.<ref name=Australian>{{cite news|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/sport/football/aiden-oneill-credits-a-dog-with-honing-his-attacking-skills/news-story/7df66fa3408e206bccb6358ce9d63467?login=1|title=Aiden O'Neill credits a dog with honing his attacking skills|newspaper=[[The Australian]]|date=17 June 2017|accessdate=18 June 2017|author=Gatt, Ray}}</ref>

==Club career==
O'Neill played youth football for Brisbane Athletic between 2008 and 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/brisbaneathleticfc/photos/a.223634841178333.1073741835.191833267691824/499477400260741/?type=3&theater|title=Brisbane Athletic Football Club|publisher=[[Facebook]]|date=23 August 2016|accessdate=23 August 2016}}</ref> He moved to England as a teenager, where he sought to pursue a career in football.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.footballaustralia.com.au/article/the-story-behind-burnleys-epl-debutant-from-australia/103t1yfkxmvkf1na0dy53az6qg|title=The story behind Burnley's EPL debutant from Australia|publisher=[[Football Federation Australia]]|date=25 August 2016|accessdate=28 August 2016}}</ref>

On 12 January 2016, O'Neill signed his first professional contract with then-[[Football League Championship|Championship]] side [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]].<ref>{{cite news|title=O'Neill Signs Professional Deal|url=http://www.burnleyfootballclub.com/news/article/oneill-signs-professional-deal-2897325.aspx|accessdate=20 August 2016|work=Burnley Football Club|date=12 January 2016|archive-date=21 August 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160821053205/http://www.burnleyfootballclub.com/news/article/oneill-signs-professional-deal-2897325.aspx|url-status=dead}}</ref> He made his professional debut for the club on 20 August 2016, coming on as a late substitute against [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] in the [[Premier League]] as Burnley won 2–0.<ref>{{cite web|title=Burnley 2–0 Liverpool|url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2016/08/20/england/premier-league/burnley-fc/liverpool-fc/2242031/|website=Soccerway}}</ref> He made his full debut days later, starting in an [[Overtime (sports)|extra time]] loss to [[Accrington Stanley F.C.|Accrington Stanley]] in the [[EFL Cup]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/37103144|publisher=[[BBC Sport]]|date=24 August 2016|accessdate=25 August 2016|title=Accrington Stanley 1–0 Burnley (AET)}}</ref>

In January 2017, he joined [[EFL League One]] strugglers [[Oldham Athletic A.F.C.|Oldham Athletic]] on loan until the end of the season.<ref>{{Cite news |title=O'Neill Makes Loan Move To Oldham |url=http://www.burnleyfootballclub.com/news/article/2016-17/oneill-makes-loan-move-to-oldham-3548336.aspx |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170131213131/http://www.burnleyfootballclub.com/news/article/2016-17/oneill-makes-loan-move-to-oldham-3548336.aspx |url-status=dead |archive-date=31 January 2017 |publisher=Burnley Official Site |date=31 January 2017 |accessdate=31 January 2017 }}</ref> He made a total of fifteen appearances for the Latics.<ref name="Soccerway"/>

In August 2017, he joined League One side [[Fleetwood Town F.C.|Fleetwood Town]] on a season-long loan deal.<ref>{{cite news |title=Aiden O'Neill: Fleetwood Town sign Burnley midfielder on season-long loan|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/40789649 |work=BBC Sport |date=1 August 2017 |accessdate=14 August 2017}}</ref> In January 2018, he returned to Burnley early having made twenty-seven appearances and scoring once against [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]].<ref>{{Cite news |title=Aiden O'Neill returns to Burnley|url=https://www.fleetwoodtownfc.com/news/2018/january/aiden-oneill-returns-to-burnley/ |publisher=Fleetwood Town F.C. |date=2 January 2018 |accessdate=9 January 2018}}</ref>

In August 2018, O'Neill returned to Australia to play for [[Central Coast Mariners FC|Central Coast Mariners]] in the [[A-League]] on a season-long loan.<ref>{{cite news|date=15 August 2018|accessdate=15 August 2018|title=Burnley midfielder O'Neill returns home to Central Coast Mariners|url=https://www.burnleyexpress.net/sport/football/clarets/burnley-midfielder-o-neill-returns-home-to-central-coast-mariners-1-9301886|newspaper=[[Burnley Express]]|author=Boden, Chris}}</ref>

=== Melbourne City ===
O'Neill signed a three-year deal with [[Melbourne City FC|Melbourne City]] in September 2020.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.a-league.com.au/news/melbourne-city-fc-signs-australian-u23-midfielder-aiden-oneill|title=Melbourne City FC signs Australian U23 midfielder Aiden O'Neill|website=[[A-League]]|accessdate=9 September 2020|date=9 September 2020}}</ref>

During the 22/23 season O'Neill had become a key player in the starting 11, scoring a brace in a 2–1 victory against [[Brisbane Roar]] on 12 March 2023.

During the [[Melbourne City v Melbourne Victory (17 December 2022)|Melbourne Derby on the 17 December 2022]], O'Neill scored the opening goal during the match, that was later abandoned due to player safety in the 22nd minute. During the resumption of the match on 5 April 2023, O'Neill scored a second goal completing his brace. His brace became the longest time between both goals in a brace with his first and second goal being 156,956 minutes apart.<ref>{{cite web |title=156,956 MINUTES OF PERSEVERANCE: AIDEN O'NEILL'S WORLD RECORD |url=https://melbournecityfc.com.au/news/156956-minutes-of-perseverance-aiden-oneills-world-record |website=Melbourne City FC |date=7 April 2023 |access-date=15 January 2024}}</ref>
