=== New York City FC === 
In April 2025, Aiden O’Neill transferred from Standard Liège to [[New York City FC]], signing a contract that runs through the 2028 season.<ref>https://www.reuters.com/sports/soccer/new-york-city-fc-sign-aussie-m-aiden-oneill-through-28-2025-04-25/</ref> Sporting Director David Lee highlighted O’Neill’s leadership and familiarity with the City Football Group system as key assets, noting his role as a “smart and powerful midfielder with a high work rate.”<ref>https://www.newyorkcityfc.com/news/new-york-city-fc-signs-midfielder-aiden-o-neill-from-belgian-side-standard-liege</ref>

He made his MLS debut in the early part of the 2025 season, adding six appearances by June 2025.<ref>https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aiden_O%27Neill</ref> Seamlessly transitioning into NYCFC's midfield rotation, O’Neill brought international experience, having previously captained Standard Liège and earned numerous caps with the Australia national team.<ref>https://www.socceroos.com.au/news/aiden-oneill-seals-mls-deadline-day-switch-new-york-city-fc</ref>


==International career==
[[File:4822286 AE7I6649 - Aiden O'Neill.jpg|thumb|right|200px|O'Neill lining up for [[Australia men's national soccer team|Australia]] at the [[2023 AFC Asian Cup]].]]

O'Neill has stated that his preference is to play for Australia, but had not been in any contact with [[Football Federation Australia]] when he made his Premier League debut in August 2016.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://theworldgame.sbs.com.au/article/2016/09/02/premier-league-whizkid-oneill-dreaming-socceroos-call|title=Premier League whizkid O'Neill dreaming of Socceroos call|publisher=[[The World Game]]|date=2 September 2016|accessdate=3 September 2016|author=Lewis, Dave}}</ref> He was later called up for an [[Australia men's national under-23 soccer team|Australia under-23]] camp in March 2017.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/sport/football/deni-juric-the-younger-brother-of-socceroos-striker-tomi-selected-for-olyroos-camp-in-spain/news-story/c3fb827ec291f3913266a609b3f872ec|title=Deni Juric, the younger brother of Socceroos striker Tomi, selected for Olyroos camp in Spain|author=Davutovic, David|newspaper=[[Herald Sun]]|date=15 March 2017|accessdate=13 June 2017}}</ref> He had previously been contacted by the [[Football Association of Ireland]] and the [[Irish Football Association]] but reiterated that his preference was to play for Australia.

On 14 March 2023, O’Neill was called up to the [[Australia men's national soccer team|Socceroos]] team for the first time with friendlies against [[Ecuador national football team|Ecuador]].

He made his senior debut in a 3–1 win over Ecuador on 24 March 2023.

On February 3, 2024, O'Neill received his first international red card against [[South Korea national football team|South Korea]] in extra-time at the quarter-finals of the [[2023 AFC Asian Cup]]. The game would end in a 1–2 loss.<ref>{{cite web |title= Socceroos lose 2–1 to South Korea in extra time of Asian Cup quarterfinal after conceding two late penalties |url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2024-02-03/socceroos-take-on-south-korea-in-asian-cup-quarterfinal/103413120 |website=ABC News |access-date=3 February 2024 |language=en |date=3 February 2024}}</ref> He has since become a mainstay in the Socceroos squad, featuring prominently in Australia's third round of [[2026_FIFA_World_Cup_qualification_–_AFC_third_round#Group_C|2026 FIFA World Cup qualifiers]].

